            </rs>.</p>
               <p>JAMES MASON. I am a <rs id="t18260914-241-viclabel1381" type="occupation">baker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-241-victim1343 t18260914-241-viclabel1381"></join>. On the 3d of July I was in <placeName id="t18260914-241-crimeloc1382">Shoreditch</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-241-crimeloc1382" type="placeName" value="Shoreditch"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-241-crimeloc1382" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-241-off1379 t18260914-241-crimeloc1382"></join>, between twelve and one o'clock - the brass founders were walking; I did not see who took my handkerchief, but I saw it in Bacon's hand, who was not five yards from me - a man behind me ran and collared him, and he threw it on the ground; I had not felt any pull at my pocket; it was quite safe when I was by Bishopsgate-church.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-241-person1344">
                  JOHN 
                  GIRTON
               <interp inst="t18260914-241-person1344" type="surname" value="GIRTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-241-person1344" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-241-person1344" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was going down Shoreditch, and saw Bacon take a handkerchief out of Mason's pocket; I saw him put it into his left-hand breeches' pocket; I then saw him throw it down - another man took it up - I took hold of him, and Garraway endeavoured to throw me down to get Bacon away - I had before seen them close together- Bacon could not have taken it without Garraway seeing it; Bacon got away, and I saw no more of him till one of the officers had them in custody at Guildhall.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-241-person1345">
                  ROBERT 
                  TYRRELL
               <interp inst="t18260914-241-person1345" type="surname" value="TYRRELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-241-person1345" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-241-person1345" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I saw the two prisoners together; Garraway was struggling with Girton, and they got away; Girton told me of the handkerchief being stolen; I said I knew them, and should see them again; I did not see them till the 11th, which was a week afterwards - they were then in Old-street; I followed them, and saw them commit a felony in Aldersgate-street; I knew Bacon, but Garraway had altered his dress, and got his hair cut short.</p>
               <p>BACON'S Defence. I was at Reading, in Berkshire, on that day.</p>
               <p>GARRAWAY'S Defence. I was at Clapham with my uncle.</p>
               <p>BACON - <rs id="t18260914-241-verdict1383" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18260914-241-verdict1383" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 23.</p>
